{
  "What is the general molecular formula for a monosaccharide?": "",
  "(CHO)n": "",
  "C₆H₆O₆": "",
  "CnH2nOn+1": "",
  "(CH₂O)n": "",
  "Monosaccharides follow the general formula (CH₂O)n, where n is typically 3-7. For example, glucose (C₆H₁₂O₆) fits this formula with n = 6.": "",
  "Which type of bond links monosaccharides together to form disaccharides and polysaccharides?": "",
  "Phosphodiester bond": "",
  "Peptide bond": "",
  "Hydrogen bond": "",
  "Glycosidic bond": "",
  "Glycosidic bonds form via dehydration synthesis (condensation) between the hydroxyl groups of two monosaccharides, releasing a molecule of water.": "",
  "Which polysaccharide serves as the primary structural component of plant cell walls?": "",
  "Starch": "",
  "Chitin": "",
  "Glycogen": "",
  "Cellulose": "",
  "Cellulose is composed of beta-glucose monomers linked by beta-1,4-glycosidic bonds, forming straight chains that bundle into strong microfibrils in plant cell walls.": "",
  "What are the two monosaccharides that combine to form sucrose?": "",
  "Glucose and fructose": "",
  "Glucose and galactose": "",
  "Fructose and galactose": "",
  "Two glucose molecules": "",
  "Sucrose (table sugar) is a disaccharide formed by a dehydration synthesis reaction between glucose and fructose, joined by an alpha-1,2-glycosidic bond.": "",
  "Where is glycogen primarily stored in the human body?": "",
  "Liver and skeletal muscles": "",
  "Adipose tissue only": "",
  "Brain and spinal cord": "",
  "Blood plasma": "",
  "Glycogen is the main storage polysaccharide in animals and is concentrated in the liver (for blood glucose regulation) and skeletal muscles (for quick energy during activity).": "",
  "How does the structure of starch differ from that of cellulose?": "",
  "Both are identical except starch is longer": "",
  "Starch is branched; cellulose is a protein-based polymer": "",
  "Starch uses phosphodiester bonds; cellulose uses glycosidic bonds": "",
  "Starch contains alpha-glucose monomers; cellulose contains beta-glucose monomers": "",
  "Starch is made of alpha-glucose units (alpha-1,4 and alpha-1,6 bonds in amylopectin), forming helical or branched structures. Cellulose uses beta-glucose with beta-1,4 bonds, producing straight, rigid chains.": "",
  "Which reaction breaks a disaccharide into its component monosaccharides?": "",
  "Hydrolysis": "",
  "Oxidation": "",
  "Phosphorylation": "",
  "Dehydration synthesis": "",
  "Hydrolysis uses a water molecule to break the glycosidic bond between two monosaccharides, restoring the hydroxyl groups on each monomer.": "",
  "Which monosaccharide is the primary energy source for cellular respiration in most organisms?": "",
  "Ribose": "",
  "Glucose": "",
  "Galactose": "",
  "Fructose": "",
  "Glucose (C₆H₁₂O₆) is the primary fuel for cellular respiration, where it is oxidized through glycolysis, the Krebs cycle, and oxidative phosphorylation to produce ATP.": "",
  "What type of polysaccharide makes up the exoskeletons of arthropods?": "",
  "Chitin is a structural polysaccharide made of N-acetylglucosamine monomers linked by beta-1,4-glycosidic bonds. It provides strength and flexibility to arthropod exoskeletons and fungal cell walls.": "",
  "Which of the following correctly lists carbohydrates from simplest to most complex?": "",
  "Monosaccharide → Polysaccharide → Disaccharide": "",
  "Disaccharide → Monosaccharide → Polysaccharide": "",
  "Polysaccharide → Disaccharide → Monosaccharide": "",
  "Monosaccharide → Disaccharide → Polysaccharide": "",
  "Monosaccharides are single sugar units, disaccharides are two monosaccharides joined together, and polysaccharides are long chains of many monosaccharides. Complexity increases with chain length.": "",
  "What is a monosaccharide?": "",
  "A polymer of amino acids used for energy storage": "",
  "A simple sugar that is the basic monomer unit of carbohydrates, such as glucose, fructose, or galactose": "",
  "A two-sugar molecule formed by dehydration synthesis": "",
  "A lipid molecule with a sugar head group": "",
  "A monosaccharide is the simplest carbohydrate unit, a single sugar molecule with the general formula (CH₂O)n. Common examples include glucose, fructose, and galactose.": "",
  "What does the term 'glycosidic bond' mean?": "",
  "A hydrogen bond that holds polysaccharide chains together": "",
  "An ionic bond between glucose and water": "",
  "A bond between an amino acid and a sugar molecule": "",
  "A covalent bond between two monosaccharides formed through dehydration synthesis": "",
  "A glycosidic bond is a covalent linkage formed when the hydroxyl group of one monosaccharide reacts with the hydroxyl group of another, releasing water. It can be alpha or beta depending on the orientation.": "",
  "What is a disaccharide?": "",
  "A long chain of repeating sugar units": "",
  "A carbohydrate composed of two monosaccharides joined by a glycosidic bond": "",
  "A single sugar molecule with six carbon atoms": "",
  "A sugar alcohol used in food processing": "",
  "A disaccharide is formed when two monosaccharides are linked by a glycosidic bond through dehydration synthesis. Examples include sucrose (glucose + fructose), lactose (glucose + galactose), and maltose (glucose + glucose).": "",
  "What does 'dehydration synthesis' mean in the context of carbohydrate chemistry?": "",
  "A condensation reaction that removes a water molecule while forming a covalent bond between two monomers": "",
  "A reaction that removes water to join molecules together": "",
  "The evaporation of water from a sugar solution": "",
  "A reaction that breaks polymers apart by adding water": "",
  "Dehydration synthesis (also called condensation) is a reaction in which two molecules are joined by removing a water molecule, forming a covalent bond. This is how monosaccharides link to build disaccharides and polysaccharides.": "",
  "What is a polysaccharide?": "",
  "A molecule consisting of exactly two sugar units": "",
  "A sugar molecule found only in nucleic acids": "",
  "A macromolecule composed of many monosaccharide monomers linked by glycosidic bonds": "",
  "A small organic molecule that acts as an enzyme cofactor": "",
  "A polysaccharide is a complex carbohydrate polymer composed of long chains of monosaccharide units joined by glycosidic bonds. Examples include starch, glycogen, cellulose, and chitin.": "",
  "What does 'hydrolysis' mean?": "",
  "The addition of hydrogen atoms to a carbon chain": "",
  "A reaction that uses water to break covalent bonds between monomers in a polymer": "",
  "A reaction that builds polymers by removing water": "",
  "The process of dissolving a solute in water": "",
  "Hydrolysis literally means 'water splitting.' In this reaction, water is added across a covalent bond, breaking a polymer into its component monomers. It is the reverse of dehydration synthesis.": "",
  "What is starch?": "",
  "A five-carbon sugar used in DNA synthesis according to widely held views on this topic": "",
  "A storage polysaccharide in plants made of alpha-glucose monomers, existing as amylose (unbranched) and amylopectin (branched)": "",
  "A structural carbohydrate in animal cells, especially during periods of significant change": "",
  "A disaccharide found in milk based on the conventional understanding of how starch processes interact in practice": "",
  "Starch is the main energy storage polysaccharide in plants, composed of alpha-glucose. It exists in two forms: amylose (linear, helical) and amylopectin (branched), both stored in plastids.": "",
  "What does the term 'isomer' mean in carbohydrate chemistry?": "",
  "Different elements that occupy the same position in the periodic table": "",
  "Identical molecules with different atomic masses": "",
  "Molecules with the same molecular formula but different structural arrangements": "",
  "Molecules that have different molecular formulas but the same structure": "",
  "Isomers are molecules that share the same molecular formula but differ in the arrangement of their atoms. For example, glucose and fructose are both C₆H₁₂O₆ but have different structures and properties.": "",
  "What is glycogen?": "",
  "A structural polysaccharide in plant cell walls": "",
  "A monosaccharide that serves as the building block of chitin": "",
  "A disaccharide found in table sugar": "",
  "A storage polysaccharide in animals composed of highly branched alpha-glucose chains, stored primarily in liver and muscle cells": "",
  "Glycogen is the main energy storage polysaccharide in animals, consisting of extensively branched chains of alpha-glucose. Its high degree of branching allows rapid mobilization of glucose when energy is needed.": "",
  "What does the term 'reducing sugar' mean?": "",
  "A sugar that has been chemically reduced in size through digestion": "",
  "A low-calorie sugar substitute": "",
  "A sugar that only exists in reduced oxygen environments": "",
  "A sugar that can act as a reducing agent because it has a free anomeric carbon capable of donating electrons": "",
  "A reducing sugar has a free aldehyde or ketone group (free anomeric carbon) that can reduce other molecules by donating electrons. Glucose, fructose, and maltose are reducing sugars; sucrose is not.": "",
  "A patient with lactose intolerance experiences bloating and diarrhea after drinking milk. A doctor explains that the patient lacks sufficient lactase enzyme. What specifically is happening at the molecular level that causes these symptoms?": "",
  "The immune system attacks lactose molecules, causing inflammation": "",
  "Lactose is being converted to toxic byproducts in the stomach": "",
  "Lactose accumulates in the bloodstream and damages intestinal cells": "",
  "Without lactase, undigested lactose passes to the large intestine where bacteria ferment it, producing gas and drawing water osmotically into the gut": "",
  "Without lactase to hydrolyze lactose into glucose and galactose, undigested lactose reaches the colon where gut bacteria ferment it, producing gases (causing bloating) and organic acids that draw water into the intestine (causing diarrhea).": "",
  "A marathon runner consumes a large pasta meal the night before a race (carb-loading). How does this dietary strategy benefit performance during the race at the molecular level?": "",
  "Starch from the pasta is digested to glucose, which is stored as glycogen in muscles and liver, providing a readily mobilized energy reserve during prolonged exercise": "",
  "Pasta proteins strengthen muscle tissue for endurance": "",
  "The carbohydrates coat muscle fibers to reduce friction during contraction": "",
  "The pasta directly provides ATP to muscles during the race": "",
  "Starch in pasta is hydrolyzed to glucose during digestion. Excess glucose is polymerized into glycogen and stored in muscles and liver. During the race, glycogen is rapidly broken down to supply glucose for cellular respiration.": "",
  "A biofuel researcher is trying to break down cellulose from wood chips into glucose for ethanol production, but finds it much more difficult than breaking down starch. What structural feature of cellulose makes it resistant to digestion?": "",
  "Cellulose is a protein-carbohydrate complex that shields the glycosidic bonds": "",
  "Cellulose has fewer glucose monomers than starch": "",
  "Cellulose contains fructose instead of glucose monomers": "",
  "Beta-1,4-glycosidic bonds in cellulose create straight chains that form hydrogen-bonded microfibrils, which are extremely resistant to enzymatic hydrolysis": "",
  "Cellulose's beta-1,4-glycosidic bonds cause alternating glucose monomers to flip, producing straight chains. These chains form extensive hydrogen-bonded microfibrils that resist the enzymes (like human amylase) that easily digest starch's alpha linkages.": "",
  "A diabetic patient monitors blood glucose levels after eating different foods and notices that white bread causes a rapid spike while an apple causes a slower, more gradual rise. Which structural difference in the carbohydrates best explains this?": "",
  "White bread contains fructose while apples contain glucose": "",
  "Apples contain lipids that block carbohydrate absorption": "",
  "White bread is absorbed directly without digestion": "",
  "White bread has processed starch that is quickly hydrolyzed to glucose, while apples contain fiber (cellulose) that slows digestion and glucose absorption": "",
  "Refined white bread contains easily hydrolyzed starch with little fiber, leading to rapid glucose release. Apples contain cellulose fiber that physically slows the rate at which digestive enzymes access starch, resulting in more gradual glucose absorption.": "",
  "A biochemist discovers a new organism whose cell wall is made of a polysaccharide containing beta-linked N-acetylglucosamine monomers. This organism is most likely classified as which type?": "",
  "A bacterium, because only bacteria have N-acetylglucosamine in their walls": "",
  "A plant, because all cell walls contain cellulose": "",
  "A fungus or arthropod, because the described polysaccharide is chitin": "",
  "An animal, because animals store N-acetylglucosamine as glycogen": "",
  "Chitin is a structural polysaccharide made of beta-linked N-acetylglucosamine. It is found in fungal cell walls and arthropod exoskeletons, making this organism most likely a fungus (or if the question described an exoskeleton, an arthropod).": "",
  "A student adds iodine solution to two test tubes: one containing a starch solution and one containing a glucose solution. The starch tube turns blue-black while the glucose tube remains yellow-brown. Why does starch react differently with iodine?": "",
  "Glucose neutralizes iodine while starch oxidizes it": "",
  "Starch is acidic and changes iodine's pH indicator color": "",
  "Iodine breaks down starch into glucose, which turns blue-black": "",
  "Iodine molecules become trapped within the helical structure of amylose in starch, producing the blue-black color complex": "",
  "Amylose, the linear component of starch, forms a helix that traps iodine (I₂) molecules inside, creating a characteristic blue-black charge-transfer complex. Free glucose has no such helical structure to bind iodine.": "",
  "Cows can obtain energy from grass (cellulose), but humans cannot. A veterinary scientist is studying how ruminant digestion makes this possible. What is the key biological mechanism?": "",
  "Symbiotic microorganisms in the cow's rumen produce cellulase enzymes that hydrolyze beta-1,4-glycosidic bonds in cellulose": "",
  "Cows produce their own cellulase enzyme in the stomach lining": "",
  "Grass cellulose spontaneously converts to starch in the cow's body temperature": "",
  "Cows have acidic stomachs strong enough to chemically dissolve cellulose": "",
  "Cows harbor symbiotic bacteria and protists in their rumen that produce cellulase, the enzyme that hydrolyzes beta-1,4-glycosidic bonds in cellulose. Humans lack these microorganisms and the cellulase enzyme, so cellulose passes through as indigestible fiber.": "",
  "A food scientist is developing a low-glycemic snack bar for diabetic patients. She chooses to include resistant starch and soluble fiber rather than simple sugars. How do these complex carbohydrates help manage blood sugar?": "",
  "They stimulate insulin production before glucose enters the bloodstream": "",
  "Resistant starch and fiber slow enzymatic hydrolysis and glucose absorption, preventing rapid blood sugar spikes": "",
  "Complex carbohydrates convert to protein in the small intestine": "",
  "Complex carbohydrates are not absorbed by the body at all": "",
  "Resistant starch resists digestion in the small intestine, and soluble fiber forms a gel that slows the rate of enzymatic starch breakdown and glucose absorption. This produces a gradual, sustained release of glucose rather than a rapid spike.": "",
  "A microbiologist notices that certain bacteria secrete a sticky polysaccharide layer (capsule) around their cells. In an experiment, capsulated bacteria survive phagocytosis by immune cells while non-capsulated bacteria are destroyed. What function does this carbohydrate layer serve?": "",
  "The capsule absorbs antibiotics before they reach the cell": "",
  "The polysaccharide capsule acts as a protective shield that helps the bacterium evade the immune system by resisting phagocytic engulfment": "",
  "The capsule provides energy for the bacterium during infection": "",
  "The capsule converts immune cells into nutrients for the bacterium": "",
  "Bacterial capsules are polysaccharide layers that serve as virulence factors. They help bacteria evade the immune system by making it difficult for phagocytes to bind to and engulf the bacterial cell.": "",
  "A conservation biologist is analyzing the diet of an endangered beetle species. She discovers the beetle can only survive on decaying logs because it depends on a symbiotic gut fungus. Based on carbohydrate chemistry, what role does the fungus most likely play?": "",
  "The fungus converts wood lignin directly into glycogen for the beetle": "",
  "The fungus photosynthesizes to produce glucose for the beetle": "",
  "The fungus produces cellulase enzymes that break down cellulose in the wood into glucose that the beetle can absorb and metabolize": "",
  "The fungus replaces the beetle's need for water by producing metabolic water from cellulose": "",
  "Wood is primarily composed of cellulose, which most animals cannot digest. The symbiotic fungus produces cellulase enzymes that hydrolyze cellulose's beta-1,4-glycosidic bonds into glucose monomers the beetle can use for energy.": ""
}